AGI -&nbsp; This afternoon at Palazzo Chigi, the meeting chaired by the President of the Council, Giorgia Meloni, between the government and the National Association of Magistrates. The Vice-Presidents Tajani and Salvini, the Minister of Justice Nordio and the Undersecretary of the Presidency of the Mantovano Council were present.
"At the center of the meeting, frank and fruitful - we read in a note of Palazzo Chigi - the constitutional reform on the separation of careers and the Csm to the examination of the Parliament".
"The Government has reiterated the desire to continue with determination and speed >- it reads again - in the path of implementation of the constitutional reform, wishing its approval in rapid times." &nbsp;
<div </div
"The President of the Council thanked Anm for the remarks and ideas that emerged in the debate - continues the note of Palazzo Chigi - and announced the willingness to open a discussion table > on the ordinary laws of implementation of the reform and on the document in eight points presented by the Anm, which concerns the administration of justice". &nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>Anm:&nbsp; demand for greater respect for togae
"We have taken very clear notice of a Government's will to move forward without any restraint, no modification." He declared the president of Am Cesare Parodi leaving Palazzo Chigi after the meeting with the Government.
"I was absolutely certain that nothing would come even for a reason of times: the reform cannot go back if the government wants to approve it in this legislature and then, evidently, it cannot even make a small correction otherwise it must start from the beginning of the Chambers and the times are not there," Parodi said, adding that "maybe it is better so, clarity for all, respect for all, we go forward with serenity and if the reform will be approved we will obviously be the first to apply it". &nbsp;
"I wanted to ask, in addition to the speech on the reform, a greater respect for magistrates > which are often accused of producing non-judicial but ideological measures. I strongly asked that this attitude can be changed because it is an attitude that hurts the magistrates." He underlined Parodi after the meeting at Palazzo Chigi, adding that the government "reported that politics in turn feels to be attacked to some extent. I - Parodi has continued - I have reiterated that the magistrates can wrong, that we accept the criticisms because we can wrong like all, but that we are deeply afflicted and injured when these criticisms have for object not our measures, but our ideological position that would, according to politics, conditioned our choices".
"Those really think that we are here to defend corporate interests, caste, privileges: if we do not beat these convictions, if we do not do it with extreme strength and ability, the challenge is lost from the beginning". The president of Am Cesare Parodi said this, after the meeting at Palazzo Chigi, underlining that the mobilization of the judiciary associated with the reform on the separation of careers will go on: "there will be demonstrations of various kinds, television interventions, on social, publications, brochures and meetings with people," he explained.&nbsp;
