AGI -&nbsp; Italy and Japan, protagonists of millenary civilizations, "in the decades have lived, side by side along the winding avenue of history", and after "the dark period of expansionist authoritarianism", they "built together the path of democracy and peace in the Second World War". This was said by the President of the Republic, Sergio&nbsp;Mattarella, intervening at Keidanren, the Japanese Confindustria. "Japan and Italy have been able to affirm the close link between democracy and prosperity, entering, in good law, among the industrialized countries of the G7, following principles such as freedom, respect, multilateralism," continued &nbsp;Mattarella&nbsp; in another passage of his speech the numerous challenges that are equally facing the two countries: from environmental challenge to demographic and technological development. &nbsp;
"The close relationship that unites the European Union and Japan - the Head of State has remembered - is the result of a common feeling: the awareness that only a relationship between equals in international life leads to widespread advantages and that this is based on the law and the institutions arranged for this purpose. Today the integration between the two markets is increasingly narrow," said Mattarella recalling that the economic partnership agreement (Epa), signed in 2019 between Tokyo and Brussels, "has eliminated the duties of European exports to Japan and vice versa, far from protectionisms of return". "The Japanese economy, which is among the first in the world, is so increasingly confirmed for our strategic interlocutor continent, committed as it is also in the construction of intercontinental relations that support peace, stability, prosperity."
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Mattarella said that "the idea of a free and open Indo-Pacific is essential for the development of the world and a decisive field for the lightening of tensions and the containment of pushes to the exercise of lordships in these seas. Once again the alternative is between cooperation and demand for domination." &nbsp;
The President of the Republic therefore defines the presence of Italian companies with interests in Japan and Japanese ones with interests in Italy: "Many industrial collaborations and many direct investments have been realized and the opportunities to be taken together are very numerous". Among the "positive" examples of these collaborations was the activity of the Italian-Japanese Business Group. Moreover,- he added - "I am pleased that Rome guests, next May 13th, a session dedicated to the strengthening of partnerships in the economic and commercial sector", stressing once again how the Japanese economy, at a time of "increasing challenges" both for our country and for Europe, an interlocutor and a strategic partner: "Japan and Italy have already proven to be able to unite efforts to continue to grow, together, in peace," Mattarella explained.
"The fruitful agreement of scientific and technological cooperation, carried out for almost forty years by our countries, is a framework in which hundreds of collaborations have been developed between universities and research agencies allowing to realize bilateral projects of great importance", said the president of the Republic Sergio&nbsp;Mattarella, underlining how "on these foundations, the Strategic Partnership started in 2023 stimulated further initiatives". Among these, he recalled, "the one on batteries and gravitational waves", as well as "the initiatives in the field of space, with projects dedicated to Earth observation and the exploration of the cosmos". These are experiences, said the Head of State, "which do not only benefit from the growth of our countries, but are also functional to achieving the Sustainable Development Goals set by the United Nations." And finally, hinting at Expo Osaka 2025 that will soon open its doors, Mattarella quoted the Japanese project "living Lab" to design future societies in the sign of environmental sustainability: "It is exactly what we need to find answers to the urgent questions that humanity is facing today," he concluded.
